Here's an example Java code that generates a string containing 10,000 random characters of length 100, ensuring that each character in the string is unique:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Random;

public class UniqueRandomStringGenerator {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String randomString = generateUniqueRandomString(10000, 100);
        System.out.println(randomString);
    }

    public static String generateUniqueRandomString(int stringLength, int charLength) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        Random random = new Random();
        List<Character> uniqueChars = new ArrayList<>();

        // Create a list of unique characters
        for (int i = 0; i < 65536; i++) {
            uniqueChars.add((char) i);
        }
        Collections.shuffle(uniqueChars);

        // Generate the random string
        for (int i = 0; i < stringLength; i++) {
            List<Character> tempChars = new ArrayList<>(uniqueChars);
            Collections.shuffle(tempChars);
            for (int j = 0; j < charLength; j++) {
                sb.append(tempChars.get(random.nextInt(tempChars.size())));
                tempChars.remove(sb.charAt(sb.length() - 1));
            }
        }

        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

This code uses a list of unique characters created by adding all possible characters (from 0 to 65535) and shuffling them. Then, for each character in the random string, a temporary list of characters is created by shuffling the unique character list, and one character is randomly selected from this temporary list and removed to ensure uniqueness.

